\begin_layout Subsection
Connecting to AWS and Updating the Device Shadow
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Connecting to AWS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this checkoff,
 we create an Amazon Web Services (AWS) IoT API account (for use with embedded systems),
 configure it for our CC3200 microcontroller,
 set up certificates by converting them to 
\family typewriter
.der
\family default
 or to 
\family typewriter
.pem
\family default
 files,
 and flash them to the microcontroller.
 Setting up an AWS account is simple,
 but configuring the microcontroller involves creating certificates,
 enabling policies (for HTTP GET and HTTP POST request/responses to and from the microcontroller),
 and attaching them to a device shadow,
 which is a virtual representation of the underlying hardware (a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

thing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in AWS nomenclature).
 While it is many steps,
 it allows for signifciant fine-tuned control of functionalities extended for the microcontroller,
 while ensuring that only your account is permitted to use these functionalities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next steps involve downloading the certificate keys,
 and using 
\family typewriter
OpenSSL
\family default
 to change their file extension for use in a Texas Instruments CCS environment.
 Once this is done,
 they can be flashed to the target microcontroller using the UniFlash software,
 which enables the necessary permissions needed for AWS to work with the CC3200.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This checkoff sets us up for the remainder of the lab,
 but also illustrates the steps & certificates needed to use web services in an embedded systems context,
 which is vital for using them in our Internet of Things world,
 and extending the capabilities of microcontrollers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Updating the Device Shadow
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second part of the first checkoff has us writing actual code,
 modifying an example program that uses AWS API calls to post JSON to the device shadow,
 and fetch it.
 We get some appreciation for the underlying socket and network libraries,
 and how they are used with timestamping and a WLAN connection to allow for communication between microcontroller and AWS.
 This WLAN connection comes in the form of hotspotting our computer (the machine running the microcontroller) with our phones.
 Properly using this as our Access Point involves formatting 
\family typewriter
common.h
\family default
 appropriately.
 We also get a feel for proper formatting of API endpoints in 
\family typewriter
main.c
\family default
,
 by reusing code to make an HTTP GET function.
 These details will be discussed in methods,
 but ultimately,
 we get an appreciation for TCP/IP layers and their role in communication with a cloud platform,
 and how to send HTTP API endpoints to this platform.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Checkoff Task II:
 Using SNS to Send a Message to Email
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this checkoff,
 we start to explore some of the more interesting & useful functionality that a web service can offer.
 We get a feel for AWS topics and rules,
 building blocks in the AWS ecosystems which allow a variety of protocols to trigger when our device shadow gets updated (in our case,
 an HTTP POST is sent to the shadow).
 Using the Simple Notification Service,
 an email can be sent from the device.
 We also experiment with JSON message syntax to get a clean,
 coherent email to a handle of our choice,
 using SQL-like formatting.
 This checkoff gives us an appreciation for careful I/O control of web service endpoints,
 and setting up other parts of the ecosystem that work in concert with the generic HTTP endpoints.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Checkoff Task III:
 Integrate IR Remote Texting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lastly,
 we modify our code from the final checkoff in Lab 3 to create multi-tap texting with the SNS topic,
 rule-based AWS system!
 By storing the value in a buffer,
 we can send this buffer as input to the AWS HTTP POST response (specifically when the send button is hit).
 Since both of these codebases are massive,
 a huge part of this deliverable is being able to wrap our heads around combining the functionality of each gracefully.
 The rule picks up on the posting,
 and extracts the payload,
 which then sends it over SNS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Connecting to AWS and Updating the Device Shadow
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since setting up the AWS account,
 configuring the device shadow,
 and flashing the certificates are step-by-step instructions,
 there is not many unique methods to report.
 For Windows,
 we found installing 
\family typewriter
OpenSSL v1.1.1
\family default
 with Chocolatey was the easiest approach,
 since doing so from OpenSSL's website would involve compiling Perl and building the binary ourselves.
 Save for this step,
 we follow the guide from the lab website.
 The AWS code is a much more involved process,
 and has a lot of moving parts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
First,
 the timestamp needs to be within the current month (and year) for the requests to the HTTP endpoint to work.
 We update the 
\family typewriter
MONTH
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
YEAR
\family default
 variables accordingly.
 These variables are used in 
\family typewriter
set_time()
\family default
,
 which
\family typewriter
 
\family default
invokes 
\family typewriter
sl_DevSet()
\family default
 provided by the SimpleLink library.
 This function is responsible for configuration of the CC3200's SimpleLink WiFI chip,
 a network processor.
 It will not work properly over the HTTP protocol without establishing an accurate date for the transaction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We further specify what server we are querying.
 In our case,
 the server where our device shadow lives corresponds to 
\family typewriter
a3i55f5e4s85vq-ats.iot.us-east-1.amazonaws.com
\family default
,
 which is using the US East 1 server (West Virginia) as requested in the first part of the lab.
 Tjhe destination port we are communicating over is port 
\family typewriter
8443
\family default
,
 not port 
\family typewriter
80
\family default
 (as we'd expected with an HTTP request).
 The device shadow is at 
\family typewriter
/things/ChenFeenstra-CC3200-MCU/shadow
\family default
 on the server,
 which will be is used in the headers for the HTTP requests by AWS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The CC3200 is connected to the local access point using 
\family typewriter
connectToAccessPoint()
\family default
,
 provided by the SimpleLink library.
 This local access point is a hotspot from one of our phones,
 set to 
\family typewriter
WPA
\family default
 since it is password protected.
 This is a requirement for a stable connection to the server over HTTP.
 A positive return value (
\family typewriter
lRetVal
\family default
) from the function indicates a successful connection was established.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We connect to the website with TLS encryption,
 using 
\family typewriter
tls_connect()
\family default
.
 This ensures that we can forgo the HTTPS encryption requirements,
 and use just plain HTTP to connect,
 which is better-suited (and simpler) for this lab.
 Once this connection has been established,
 we are now ready for our 
\family typewriter
HTTP POST
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
HTTP GET
\family default
 endpoints!
 We break them down next.
 We'll finish off with the logic needed to send them to the server.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
HTTP Post Anatomy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using primitive C string manipulation functions (
\family typewriter
strcpy()
\family default
,
 
\family typewriter
strlen()
\family default
) and some temporary buffers to store data,
 we can carefully construct the payload line by line,
 then send it,
 all in 
\family typewriter
http_post()
\family default
.
 This also includes newline and carriage return control characters,
 which are represented in their human-readable format.
 When all is finished,
 the payload looks like the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
POST /things/ChenFeenstra-CC3200-MCU/shadow HTTP/1.1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Host:
 a3i55f5e4s85vq-ats.iot.us-east-1.amazonaws.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Connection:
 Keep-Alive
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Content-Type:
 application/json;
 charset=utf-8
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Content-Length:
 strlen(DATA1)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
{
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
	
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

state
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 :
 {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
		
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

desired
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

:
 {
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
			
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

var
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 :
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Hello:
 phone,
 message from CC3200 via AWS IoT!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
		}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
	}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With this format,
 HTTP knows it is receiving a POST request for our shadow device,
 and it is being hosted on the specified AWS server (likely in a specific container).
 It also knows to keep the connection alive,
 to ensure it does not prematurely time out while data is still being sent over.
 It knows that the relevant data is JSON using the UTF-8 character set,
 and it also knows the length of this JSON data (so that it knows when to stop reading).
 With all of this information,
 this is ready to be serialized as a packet and sent to the AWS server.
 The JSON format will be posted to the device shadow,
 and if all is well,
 should be viewable under it's Thing entry!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sending this data over the network is as simple as invoking the 
\family typewriter
sl_Send()
\family default
 function from the SimpleLink library,
 with 4 parameters:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\family typewriter
sd
\family default
,
 the socket descriptor which specifies the active socket (obtained from the 
\family typewriter
sl_Socket()
\family default
 call,
 done under the hood in our 
\family typewriter
utils/network.c
\family default
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\family typewriter
pBuf
\family default
,
 the pointer to buffer (this is the pointer to the buffer we have prepared with the data to be sent).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\family typewriter
Len
\family default
,
 the length of the data in bytes to be sent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\family typewriter
Flags
\family default
,
 specifies optional flags.
 We set it to 
\family typewriter
0
\family default
 to ensure we are just doing a default send
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And that is it!
 At this point,
 the packet has been sent,
 and if all the configuration steps were accurate,
 the JSON will appear on the device shadow after calling 
\family typewriter
POST
\family default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
HTTP Get Anatomy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The anatomy and packet serialization for the 
\family typewriter
GET
\family default
 endpoint is virtually identical to 
\family typewriter
POST
\family default
.
 The only change is the first header in the payload,
 which is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
GET /things/ChenFeenstra-CC3200-MCU/shadow HTTP/1.1
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In our program flow,
 
\family typewriter
POST
\family default
 is called first.
 Once this is posted,
 
\family typewriter
GET
\family default
 uses the same payload and retrieves it.
 This all happens in 
\family typewriter
http_get()
\family default
.
 With the exception of the different header,
 the logic is the same as 
\family typewriter
http_post()
\family default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Using SNS to Send a Message to Email
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now use Simple Notification Service (SNS) over AWS,
 a lightweight messaging protocol,
 to send an e-mail to an account of our choice using the microcontroller.
 This requires some configuration specific to the web service.
 AWS is organized into modules to perform functions on IoT devcies;
 SNS allows for push messages!
 We create an SNS topic,
 then a subscription for it with the 
\emph on
EMAIL
\emph default
 protocol for texting,
 and specify an endpoint to receive these messages (in this case,
 we each used our UC Davis emails).
 Once we confirm the subscription for this email,
 we are ready to start pushing messages.
 The topic created ends up being
\family typewriter
 $aws/things/ChenFeenstra-CC3200-MCU/shadow/update/accepted
\family default
.
 We'll see how this plays with the IoT rule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now,
 we can also set up an IoT rule for this SNS topic.
 The nature of the rule means that the specified message will be sent every time the device shadow is updated (in the nature of our program,
 when it receives an HTTP endpoint).
 We specifically set up an ACT (Message Routing rule).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tricky part is getting the formatting just right.
 AN SQL statement can be used to improve on this format.
 The one we found that resulted in a clean,
 JSON-schema free format in our email is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
SELECT VALUE state.desired.message FROM '$aws/things/ChenFeenstra-CC3200-MCU/shadow/update/accepted'
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This specific SQL extracts the value of the JSON message from our topic,
 recursing into the relevant part of the JSON.
 It takes this message from an attribute in the device shadow.
 Once we run our program again,
 we get the message 
\family typewriter

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Hello phone,
 message from CC3200 via AWS IoT!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 via e-mail.

\family default
 
\end_layout

